<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-01-28T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-01-28T21:00:00-05:00" n="392" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d392">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">693.0023/1–2947: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Dairen</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Benninghoff</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                            the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Dairen</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-01-29T11:00:00+09:00">January 29,
                                1947—11 a.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received January 31—6:56 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>19. Although visit of courier ship was without incident and superficially
                        cordial, Dept should know that only one officer was allowed ashore. Doctor
                        denied permission visit Vice Consul Patch’s ill daughter, sailors throwing
                        football on dock ordered back on ship. Would appreciate information
                        treatment Soviet ships U. S. controlled ports.</p>
                    <p>Repeat Nanking, Shanghai, Moscow.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Benninghoff</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>